						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/Reshaping-tertiary-agricultural-education/Related-developments/Launch-of-a-new-African-Plant-Breeding-Academy" title="Launch of a new African Plant Breeding Academy" alt="link">Launch of a new African Plant Breeding Academy</a></h2>

	
					<p>The University of California at Davis, in collaboration with the African Union’s New Partnership for Africa’s Development (NEPAD) and the African Orphan Crops Consortium launched the &nbsp;African Plant Breeding Academy. The Academy is designed to train a generation of plant breeders who will help improve the nutritional value of indigenous African crops. The Consortium (of &nbsp;which the Academy is part) aims to sequence the genomes of 96 indigenous orphan crops that are important for African diets (African eggplant, potato, cocoyam, Ethiopian mustard, as well &nbsp;as cassava, cacao, millet, sorghum and legumes, among others). Participating African plant breeders at the new academy will be trained in the most advanced theory and technologies for &nbsp;plant breeding, quantitative genetics, statistics and experimental design, in support of critical decisions for crop improvement.(UC Davis, 20/06/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/Reshaping-tertiary-agricultural-education/Related-developments/Launch-of-a-new-African-Plant-Breeding-Academy">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/Reshaping-tertiary-agricultural-education/Related-developments/How-can-universities-influence-development-policy" title="How can universities influence development policy? " alt="link">How can universities influence development policy? </a></h2>

	
					<p>Members of the Evidence-Based Policy in Development Network (EBPDN) debated what universities could do to get their academic research ‘out there’. Some interesting suggestions included: ‘collective action as no single or isolated sector in society can accomplish the desired changes’, ‘updating the universities’ methods and contents so students grasp the fast-changing world of knowledge’, ‘creating policy research institutes to focus research on priority areas’ and ‘conducting research that respond to issues that are policy relevant’. Three specific strategies were suggested: (1) working with public officials to enhance and/or find ways to improve the implementation mechanism; (2) engaging in policy debates that address priority issues; and (3) having student conduct local needs assessment and share results with policymakers and local communities.<a href="http://www.drussa.net/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=1931" target="_self">http://www.drussa.net/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=1931</a> (Drussa, 28/05/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">2/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/Reshaping-tertiary-agricultural-education/Related-developments/How-can-universities-influence-development-policy">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/Reshaping-tertiary-agricultural-education/Related-developments/Central-America-and-the-Caribbean-to-update-their-agricultural-R-D-indicators" title="Central America and the Caribbean to update their agricultural R&amp;D indicators " alt="link">Central America and the Caribbean to update their agricultural R&amp;D indicators </a></h2>

	
					<p>The project aims at updating the information on agricultural research and development in the two regions, in order to highlight the need for increased investment in those areas. The IFPRI/ASTI–CIAT–IICA Training and Implementation Workshop ‘Monitoring of capabilities and investments in agricultural R&amp;D in Central America and the Caribbean’ took place 19-20 March 2013. Staff of the research institutes designated as focal points in each country are being trained in the methodology used by the ASTI, to ensure that the data is compiled scientifically and the information from the different countries is comparable.&nbsp; (<a href="http://www.iica.int/Eng/prensa/pages/comunicadoprensav1.aspx?cp=856?utm_source=K4DNewsletterEN&amp;utm_medium=Link&amp;utm_campaign=K4D_EN_April2013" target="_blank">IICA</a>, 09/04/2013)&nbsp;</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/05/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Policy/Reshaping-tertiary-agricultural-education/Related-developments/Central-America-and-the-Caribbean-to-update-their-agricultural-R-D-indicators">Read more...</a>
</div>
